@node INFO "What is this ?"

    @{FG shine}- Introduction -@{FG text}


  @{b}YamExpansion@{ub} is a program to handles emails from the @{b}Aminet@{ub} mailing list.
 You can view in a GUI the uploaded files, select your favourite files
 and then make an ftp-mail, or a @{b}WGet@{ub} script, or an @{b}AmFtp@{ub} batch file, or
 an HTML file.

  Remember also that this software is @{b}freeware@{ub}, so you can copy it and
 use it without pay anything, you can spread this program only in his original
 format (i.e. this archive).


@endnode


@node CONFIG "Settings Window"

    @{FG shine}- Settings Window -@{FG text}


  In this window you can set some variables of the program. To access to this
 window you must click on the @{b}Settings@{ub} button in the @{"main window" link MWIN}.

  @{FG shine}@{b}HTML File:@{ub}@{FG text}

     @{b}Aminet Url:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the complete Aminet URL in browser
                  format. Note that you must include also the Aminet remote directory

                    @{b}ex:@{ub} ftp://ftp.unina.it/pub/aminet/

     @{b}Save htmls:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose a drawer where you want to save
      @{b}in drawer@{ub}   all the Html files created with YamExpansion

   @{b}Fancy tables:@{ub}  if you select this option then the generated Html file will contain
                  elaborated but slow tables. If you unset this option tables will
                  looks like the normal email, but with links to files

  @{b}Send html file:@{ub} send the just created html file to your preferred browser using the
      @{b}to browser@{ub}  @{b}OpenURL.library@{ub} (see the @{b}OpenURL.library@{ub} preference program to set
                  your preferred browser)

  @{b}show/uniconify:@{ub} if the browser is iconified then it will be uniconified
         @{b}browser@{ub}

   @{b}bring browser:@{ub} will bring browser window to front
        @{b}to front@{ub}

    @{b}open file in:@{ub} open file in new window if none is free
      @{b}new window@{ub}

  @{b}launch browser:@{ub} will launch the browser if it's not running
@{b}when not running@{ub}


  @{FG shine}@{b}AmFtp Batch File:@{ub}@{FG text}

     @{b}Aminet Dir:@{ub}  here you can insert the remote Aminet directory

                    @{b}ex:@{ub} /pub/aminet/

     @{b}Batch file:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the file name for the batch file
           @{b}name@{ub}   to use in AmFtp

       @{b}Download:@{ub}  if you select this option then you'll download also the .readme
        @{b}.readme@{ub}   file for each file you select

    @{b}always open:@{ub}  if you select this option, the program will always open a requester and
      @{b}requester@{ub}   ask you for a file name when you press on @{b}Make AmFtp Batch@{ub}

      @{b}Append to:@{ub}  if you select this option, when an existing AmFtp batch file
 @{b}existing batch@{ub}   exists then new archives selected will be added to this file.
           @{b}file@{ub}   If the file doesn't exist it will be created.

      @{b}Use Miami:@{ub}  this is for use Miami as TCP-IP stack in the automatic download ARexx script.
                  So if Miami is not loaded in memory the script will automatically launch it and go
                  online (if not yet online), otherwise the script will simply go online (if not yet
                  online).

     @{b}What to do:@{ub}  here you can choose what to do after the download is done. If you choose the last
          @{b}after@{ub}   option ("Let me choose bla bla bla") then a requester will appear before the download
                  where you can select Stay online, Go offline, Go offline quit Miami or cancel the
                  download.

          @{b}Miami:@{ub}  the Miami excutable file (used to lauch it in the ARexx script)
     @{b}executable@{ub}

    @{b}FTP Program:@{ub} select the program to use for automatic download (AmFTP or DOpusII)
         @{b}to use@{ub}

  @{b}AmFTP/DOpusII:@{ub}  the AmFTP excutable file (used to lauch it in the ARexx script)
     @{b}executable@{ub}

 @{b}Aminet FTP URL:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the complete Aminet URL in FTP
                  format. Note that the remote directory is the same as "Aminet Dir" above.

                    ex: ftp.unina.it

  @{b}Save files in:@{ub}  select the directory in which files will be downloaded

  @{b}Download what:@{ub}  here you can choose what to download with the automatic ARexx script. If you choose
                  the last one ("Let me choose bla bla bla") then a requester will appear before the
                  download where you can select between the first 3 options or cancel the download.
                  Also note that if you don't select nothing and you choose the first 2 options than
                  the script will download only the old AmFTP batch file. If you don't select nothing
                  and there is no batch file than the script will go in execution but will download nothing.



  @{FG shine}@{b}WGet Script:@{ub}@{FG text}

     @{b}Aminet Url:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the complete Aminet URL in browser
                  format. Note that you must include also the Aminet remote directory

                    @{b}ex:@{ub} ftp://ftp.unina.it/pub/aminet/

    @{b}Script file:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the file name for the WGet script
           @{b}name@{ub}   file. To execute it you must use a shell: go to the directory
                  where you saved it and write its name. The files will be downloaded
                  in this directory (I suggest you to make a download directory and
                  to save scripts in this directory and to put the WGet executable in
                  C: drawer)

       @{b}Download:@{ub}  if you select this option then you'll download also the .readme
        @{b}.readme@{ub}   file for each file you select

    @{b}always open:@{ub}  if you select this option, the program will always open a requester and
      @{b}requester@{ub}   ask you for a file name when you press on @{b}Make WGet Script@{ub}

      @{b}Append to:@{ub}  if you select this option when an existing WGet script file
@{b}existing script@{ub}   exists then new archives selected will be added to this file.
                  If the file doesn't exist it will be created.

    @{b}build script:@{ub} if you select this option you'll create a file with the list of archives and
   @{b}and file list@{ub}  a script with the single "wget -c -i <filelist>" line. All the archives will be
                  added to the file list and you can choose a name for this file, see below...

    @{b}Name of file:@{ub} here you can choose the name for the file list
            @{b}list@{ub}


  @{FG shine}@{b}Ftp-Mail:@{ub}@{FG text}

      @{b}Ftp-Email:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the email of the Ftp-Email server
 @{b}server address@{ub}   you want to use

     @{b}Aminet Url:@{ub}  here you can insert or choose the Aminet URL in normal format

                    @{b}ex:@{ub} ftp.unina.it

     @{b}Aminet Dir:@{ub}  here you can insert the remote Aminet directory

                    @{b}ex:@{ub} /pub/aminet/

       @{b}Download:@{ub}  if you select this option then you'll download also the .readme
        @{b}.readme@{ub}   file for each file you select


 @{b}Attachment size:@{ub} here you can select the size of file attached to the emails:
                  some servers support @{b}size huge@{ub} (512 kbytes), others @{b}size num[K|M]@{ub} where
                  @{b}num@{ub} is the numeric size expressed in @{b}K@{ub}ilobytes or @{b}M@{ub}egabytes. Note that
                  you must be sure that your server support one of these settings.

  @{b}Attach file as:@{ub} you can select how file will be attached to the emails: as @{b}MIME@{ub} or
                  @{b}UUEncode@{ub}d.

  @{b}Use Reply to:@{ub}   field: select this option to add a Reply to: field to your
                  ftp-emails

  @{b}Reply to: address:@{ub} here you can insert your preferred Reply to: email
                     address



  @{FG shine}@{b}Misc Settings:@{ub}@{FG text}

  @{b}Average Modem:@{ub}  here you can insert the average speed of your connection.
          @{b}Speed@{ub}   YamExpansion will use this value to calculate the expected
                  download time in the main window.

   @{b}set recent as:@{ub} the recent email will be set as read while quitting
      @{b}read while@{ub}  YamExpansion
        @{b}quitting@{ub}

  @{b}quit after you:@{ub} after you press one of the four "make" buttons (Make FtpMail, Make
@{b}press one of the@{ub}  AmFtp Batch, Make WGet Script, Make Html) the program will quit
@{b}4 "make" buttons@{ub}  itself.

  @{b}recents are in:@{ub} if your recents are in folders packed with XPK then you must select
      @{b}XPK-Packed@{ub}  this option. Note that the program will automatically detect if an email
         @{b}folders@{ub}  is packed or not, I've added this option only to speed up the program for
                  who doesn't use XPK-Packed folders

     @{b}move origin:@{ub} if you select this option, when you add items to the list of selected
      @{b}list items@{ub}  files, then these items will be deleted from the files in the email

   @{b}Recent sender:@{ub} here you can insert the sender of the recent emails. In this way, if the Aminet
                  server changes in the future, you can always adapt the program to the new server.


  @{b}Use@{ub}, @{b}Save@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} buttons are used to... use, save and cancel the current
 settings :)

@endnode

@node HOWUSE "Usage"

  To use @{b}YamExpansion@{ub}, first @{"install" link INST} the program, then you can proceed:

 @{FG shine}1.@{FG text} start Yam2.0

 @{FG shine}2.@{FG text} select one or more recent emails

 @{FG shine}3.@{FG text} start YamExpansion (you can start from shell, from its icon, from the Scripts
    menu or automatically. It depends on how you @{"install" link INST} the program)

 @{FG shine}4.@{FG text} read the section named @{"main window" link MWIN} to know how to use all the gadgets of the
    program

  @{FG shine}@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{FG text} if you run the program from the shell please run it with the
 @{b}run yamexpansion@{ub} command, otherwise it will run one time and then crash :(

@endnode



@node MWIN "Main Window"

    @{FG shine}- Main Window -@{FG text}


   When you start @{b}YamExpansion@{ub}, the main window of the program will appear.
  As you can note, this window is structured in many sections: on the top of
  the window you can see the type of the recent and it's date. On the same line you can
  note three buttons: two arrows used to read the @{b}next@{ub}/@{b}previous@{ub} recent (if you are reading
  a daily one, the new recent will be a daily one too, the same appens with weekly ones) and
  an @{b}R@{ub} button to read the currently selected recents in Yam folder (same restrictions of arrow
  buttons apply here).

   Slightly below, there is the @{b}List of Files in the email@{ub}. If the email is a
  weekly one, then you can find three buttons used to select one of the three
  sections of a weekly recent email: @{b}Weekly Uploads@{ub}, @{b}Most Downloaded@{ub} of the week
  and the @{b}Aminet Chart@{ub} of the most rated archives.

   When you start @{b}YamExpansion@{ub} the list will be filled with all the archives in
  the email. In this list you can select an entry or multiselect many entries and
  then add these with the @{b}Add File(s)@{ub} button to the second list (see below). You
  can also drag&drop entries in this list with the mouse in order to sort them (for
  now you cannot drag&drop entries in the list below, sorry :P) If you want to add
  all the files listed you can click on @{b}Add All Files@{ub}.

   Below the Add buttons you can see two counters: one shows the total number of
  files in the list and the other the total size of files in bytes form.


   In the second section of the Gui you find the @{b}List of Selected Files@{ub}. The files
  contained in this list are the files you want to download from Aminet. But if you
  want to remove one of more files you can select or multiselect these and then press
  on the @{b}Remove File(s)@{ub} button. If you press on @{b}Remove All Files@{ub}, you'll clear all
  the list. Like in the list above, here you can drag&drop one or more files with
  mouse in order to sort them as you want.

   Below the Remove buttons you can see three counters: the first shows the total
  number of files in the list, the second shows the total size of files in bytes
  form and the last shows the expected download time for these files (see @{"Settings" link CONFIG}
  to know how this value is calculated)..

   When you have selected the files you want to download, you can choose in which
  way you want to download them: @{b}Make FtpMail@{ub} will make an email in which the files
  are listed (you'll receive the files in an email, so be carefull), @{b}Make AmFtp@{ub}
  @{b}Batch@{ub} will make a batch file to use with AmFtp, @{b}Make WGet Script@{ub} will make a
  script that uses the WGet program (not included) to donwload the files and finally
  @{b}Make Html@{ub} will make an Html file that contains a list of the files each of them
  with a link to download it. On the right of Make AmFtp Batch and Make WGet Script
  buttons there are two tiny buttons to edit the batch file and the script. If you want
  to delete the Amftp batch file you can use the @{b}Delete Amftp batch@{ub} option in the @{b}Project@{ub}
  menu; to delete the WGet script use the @{b}Delete WGet script@{ub} option in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu.
  The @{b}D@{ub} button on the right of Make AmFtp Batch is used to create an ARexx script that will automatically
  download the files selected, the batch file or both.
  (Note: see @{"settings" link CONFIG} section for more details on file names and directories)

   If the email contains more text (usually some informations on Aminet servers or
  Aminet cds) then you'll find here a window text. No text = No window :)

   On the bottom of the GUI there is a @{b}status bar@{ub} where you can read some
  informations about the current status of the program. (always watch it :)
  And on its right you can find the Settings button to open the @{"settings window" link CONFIG}.

   @{b}Please@{ub}, before using the program, take a moment to configure it, just click
  on the @{b}Settings@{ub} button (read more about settings @{"here" link CONFIG}).

@endnode


@node FAQ "F.A.Q."

  The most Frequently Asked Questions:

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} Why YamExpansion is not translated in my language ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} If you want you can do it for you by editing the file @{b}yamexpansion.ct@{ub} file
      in this archive and then sending it to me (if you want you can translate
      also the .guide file ;)

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} What is the Recent Mailing List ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} It's a free, read-only mailing list in which the emails contain a list of
      the files uploaded to Aminet. There are two mailing lists: one for the
      daily uploads (you'll receive an email every day) and one for the uploads
      during the week (you'll receive an email every week (at saturday)).

       You can subscribe to this mailing lists sending an email to @{b}listproc@wugate.wustl.edu@{ub}

       with @{b}SUBSCRIBE AMINET-DAILY <your-email-address>@{ub} in the body for the daily one
       or with @{b}SUBSCRIBE AMINET-WEEKLY <your-email-address>@{ub} in the body for the
       weekly one.

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} What is @{b}WGet@{ub} ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} WGet is a program mainly used to download files from the WWW and to make
      mirrors of WWW sites. But WGet is very useful to download files from ftp
      servers because it can continue interrupted downloads automatically (also
      for files on the WWW). You must only write in the shell: @{b}wget -c <url>@{ub}

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} Where can I find WGet and how can I install it ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} WGet is a free program included in the ADE (@{i}Amiga Developer Environment@{ui})
      Project. You can find it on the Geek Gadgets cds or on Geek Gadgets site
      (or mirror, I suggest you the ftp.unina.it mirror). To install WGet simply
      put the executable wget in C: and if you want wget.guide in a directory.

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} How can I use batch files with @{b}AmFtp@{ub} ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} Load AmFtp, in the @{b}Project@{ub} menu select @{b}Batch Window@{ub}, in the Settings menu
      select @{b}Load & add batch window contents@{ub} and select your batch file. Then
      the files will appear in the @{b}Batch Window@{ub}, now you cannot connet to an
      Aminet server and when you are in press @{b}Receive all@{ub} button in the Batch
      Window.

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} Where can I find the @{b}OpenURL.library@{ub} ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} On Aminet in the /comm/www/ directory with the name openurl@{FG shine}xx@{FG text}.lha, where @{FG shine}xx@{FG text}
      is the number of the available versione (at the moment it's 20)

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} Can I remove the assignment ?

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} Yes, from this version you can

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} The program crashes with a Line 1111 Emulation error

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} You're using a very old version of SetPatch, download a recent one from
      http://www.amiga.de (10x to Matteo Cavalleri for reporting this "bug" :)))

   @{FG shine}Q:@{FG text} When I start the program, it tells me @{i}"This is not a recent email"@{ui} but I'm sure the email
      is a recent... so ? :)

   @{FG shine}A:@{FG text} It's probable that the Aminet mailing list server has changed. To adapt the program you
      cannot change the server from the settings window because the program doesn't start, but
      you can modify the settings file:

       @{FG shine}1.@{FG text} open with a texteditor the @{b}envarc:yamexpansion.prefs@{ub}

       @{FG shine}2.@{FG text} go to line @{b}34@{ub}

       @{FG shine}3.@{FG text} change the line with the new complete name server. To obtain this name:

          @{FG shine}a.@{FG text} open Yam

          @{FG shine}b.@{FG text} place the cursor on a recent email

          @{FG shine}c.@{FG text} open a shell

          @{FG shine}d.@{FG text} execute the command: @{b}rx "options results;address YAM; MAILINFO STEM f.; say f.from"@{ub}

          @{FG shine}e.@{FG text} in the shell will appear the complete name of the sender, copy it in the
             texteditor at line 34

       @{FG shine}4.@{FG text} save the file

       @{FG shine}5.@{FG text} reboot your Amiga or if you prefere copy the file envarc:yamexpansion.prefs in env:

       @{FG shine}6.@{FG text} now you can load YamExpansion :P

@endnode
